1. Overview

This is an exploratory report on juvenile snoeshoe hares (Lepus americanus) using data collected during the US Long Term Ecological Research Network's study on Snowshoe hare physical data in the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest. Using the data collected from 1999-2012, this report will analyze the counts and sizes of juvenile hares. This report will also compare the weights of juvenile hares ccording to sex, and perform a simple linear analysis on the relationship between hind foot length and body mass.

2. Data and Methods

Snowshoe hare data and measurements were made accessible through Knut Kielland and associates at the Bonanza Creek LTER. The data contain measurements and observations on hares during a capture-recapture study done in Alaska's Tanana valley from 1999-2012. Following exploratory data visualization, body mass measurements between male and female juvenile showshoe hares are compared using a two-sample t-test using a significance level () of 0.05 throughout. Differences between groups are described by a Cohen's d effect size. The relationship between body mass and hind foot length is explored by simple linear regression. All analysis are in R version 3.6.3 and R Studio Version 1.1.463

Above, Figure 1 shows the number of hares caught each year of the survey period. The number of hares caught vaired between 0 and 126. The minimum is 2, and the maximum is 126. The mean number of hares caught is 31.5, and the median is 18.5. The graph shows that the number of hares caught peaked at the beginning of the study in 1999. After this peak the number decreased until the first 0 catch year is recorded in 2002. The count then stayed below 50, with around every other year reaching 50, with low catch number in between. The second year of 0 caught occured in 2009, with the last three years of the survey seeing counts below 25. Ensuring that both the number of traps, and days of of the year the traps are set are equal and consistent accross the survey's years can help reduce variance resulting from the studies methods.

Juvenile Hare Weights

Figure 2 and Figure 3 above show the comparison between female and male juevenile showshoe hare weights first in a jitter plot and then in a side by sire histograms. Samples taken where sex was not recorded are represented by 'NA'. In the jitter plot, the hares are separated by the site they were caught at, and it is clear that the least number of hares caught was at the Bonbs, and the most at the Bonrip site. At the Bonrip site, the female weights are more concentrated, and the male weights are more spread out. This is shown further in the histogram, where the percent female weights adhere to a more normal curve, and the male weights have a larger spread with less of a notable peak. The weights values do not vary largely between the sexes, or between site location.

In this section we compared the weights of juvenile showshoe hares based on sex using a unpaired t-test, a Cohen's test to see the effect size, and using summary statistics.

Mean weight for female juvenile hares (NA g) is less than that for male juvenile hares (946 g). The effect size is small, with a Cohen's D of (Cohen's d = NA). The difference between the means is significant (two-sample t-test, t = NA, p < 0.01)

Getting a p-value of 0.0070933 means that there is a 0.7% chance of getting means that are at least as different as those seen here if they're drawn from populations with the same mean. This means that we would reject the null hypothesis that the population's mean weights are the same.

Juvenile Weight & Hind Foot Length

Simple linear regression was used to explore the relationship between juvenile snowshoe hare hindfoot lenth (mm) and body weight (g) across all three sampling sites, including both male and female hares. A regression model was found (\(\beta\) = 9.523, F(1,247) = 105.2, p < 0.001) with an R2 of 0.299.

With this linear regression, the R2 value of 0.2987695 means that only 29.8769547% of the variance is in body mass is predictable from the change in hindfoot length.

Using a Pearson's R correlation, we see that there is a moderatley strong correlation between juvenile hare hind foot length and body weight (r = 0.55, t(247) = 10.26, p < 0.001).

Assuming normality for these variable's relationship may cause issues, since the exploratory data visualizations showed that the residuals do not have a typical normal distribution. The linear model describes the data well to a point, but havng assumptions that are unbacked by the data can lead to irresponsible data representation and innacurate conclusions. Additionally, the sex of the juvenile hare may have an impact on this relationship, and that is a variable not addressed by this analysis.

Summary of Findings

  • The most juvenile hares were caught in the first year of the study (1999)
  • Male juvenile snowshoe hares are on average larger in bodyweight, with a mean of 945.8588957 than female juveniles, who have a mean of NA
  • Body weight appears related to hind foot length; the relationship (by simple linear regreession) has a slope (expected average increase in body mass with a 1mm increase in hind foot length) of 10.2585565
